### 1. One-Line Summary

Rakza 7 is the more linear, grounded, and value-oriented all-round offensive rubber, while Tenergy 80 is the more dynamic, elastic, and higher-ceiling rubber for aggressive topspin players who want a balance between Tenergy 05 and Tenergy 64.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown

* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rakza 7 is calmer and less springy on soft touch shots and compact strokes. Tenergy 80 has more built-in rebound and feels livelier even when you do not fully engage the sponge.
    * **Top End:** Tenergy 80 has the higher top gear. When you accelerate hard, it produces more explosive pace and a more dangerous finishing ball. Rakza 7 is fast enough for strong offensive play, but it does not reach the same upper ceiling.
    * **Linearity:** Rakza 7 is more linear and predictable from slow to hard impact. Tenergy 80 has more catapult and feels more dynamic, which gives extra power but also makes the response less flat and straightforward.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Rakza 7 is very reliable on opening loops because it grips well and gives a stable, readable launch. Tenergy 80 is also excellent here, but it rewards better timing and brush quality more clearly.
    * **Max Spin:** Tenergy 80 has the edge in maximum spin at higher swing speeds. Its topsheet-sponge combination produces heavier topspin when the player has the technique to compress and brush aggressively. Rakza 7 can still generate strong spin, but it is a step below at the highest level.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Both have strong grip, but they express it differently. Rakza 7 feels more direct and traditional in how it grabs the ball. Tenergy 80 feels more elastic and spring-assisted, especially during fast topspin exchanges.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Tenergy 80 usually gives a slightly higher and more elastic arc than Rakza 7, though it is not as distinctly high-throw as Tenergy 05. Rakza 7 has a medium-high arc that feels a bit more compact and controlled.
    * **Safety:** Rakza 7 offers excellent safety through predictability and stable trajectory control. Tenergy 80 also gives good net clearance, but because it is more lively, it can feel less forgiving for players with less precise contact.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rakza 7 feels solid, clean, and somewhat firmer in a straightforward way. Tenergy 80 feels more elastic, spring-loaded, and refined, with the characteristic Butterfly tension sensation.
    * **Dwell:** Tenergy 80 generally feels like it holds the ball a touch longer during topspin contact, especially when looping with quality acceleration. Rakza 7 has decent dwell, but the feeling is more direct and less elastic.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rakza 7 is less sensitive to incoming spin and easier to keep short in service receive and touch play. Tenergy 80 is more reactive, so it demands a more precise hand in the short game.
    * **Touch Play:** Rakza 7 is better for players who value simple control, easy drop shots, and confident pushes. Tenergy 80 can still play short very well, but it is more bouncy and needs finer touch.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rakza 7 is easier and more stable on passive blocks because it does not kick as much. Tenergy 80 can produce a more dangerous block, but it is also easier to send long if the angle is careless.
    * **Active Counter:** Tenergy 80 is better for active countering and counterlooping. Its elasticity and top-end speed help it turn incoming pace into a stronger offensive reply. Rakza 7 is competent here, but less explosive.

### 3. The Recommendation

* **Choose Rakza 7 if:**
    * You want a balanced offensive rubber with strong control and a more linear response.
    * You value short game stability, blocking ease, and predictable placement.
    * You are an intermediate to advanced player who wants quality spin and speed without the stronger catapult of the Tenergy series.
    * You prefer a rubber that is easier to manage across many situations and usually offers better value.

* **Choose Tenergy 80 if:**
    * You want a more dynamic, higher-performance rubber with stronger top-end speed and spin.
    * You are an aggressive topspin player who attacks from both wings and likes elastic rebound.
    * You want a middle ground in the Tenergy family: more balanced than Tenergy 05, but still clearly dangerous and high level.
    * You have the technique to control a livelier rubber and want more finishing power in loop-to-loop and countering exchanges.
